<h1>Router Configuration</h1>

<%=
  render_markdown(<<~MD)
    To connect to GlobalTalk, you need a router to tunnel AppleTalk traffic
    across the internet. Your AppleTalk router (distinct from your normal internet router)
    needs to know addresses of other routers to connect to.

    [AIRConfig] and [jrouter] both support loading a list of AppleTalk router
    endpoints from a text file.

    URLs are unique to each user. This keeps the door open to future customisation
    options and makes things a bit more secure. If you don't like your URL parameter,
    you can edit your profile to change it.

    [AIRConfig]: https://github.com/kalleboo/AIRConfig
    [jrouter]: https://gitea.drjosh.dev/josh/jrouter
  MD
%>

<p>URLs are unique to each user. This keeps the door open to future customisation
  and makes things a bit more secure. If you don't like your generated identifier,
  you can <%= link_to("edit your profile", [:edit, Current.user]) %> to change it.
</p>

<h2>Variants</h2>

<h3>Plain endpoints</h3>

<p>This list is the pure, unmodified list of endpoints for all available zones.
  This works well with <strong>jrouter</strong> as it'll happily resolve addresses and CNAMEs
and gracefully handle resolution failures.</p>

<p style="font-size: 1.2rem"><code><%= link_to(@all_url, @all_url) %></code></p>

<h3>Pre-resolved IP Addresses</h3>

<p><strong>MacTCP</strong> and/or <strong>Apple Internet Router</strong> can hang and have issues when hostnames
  don't cleanly resolve to an IPv4 address. If you're having that issue or
prefer a list of peers as IPv4 addresses, use this list which
will only return resolved endpoint IPs. This can take longer to generate.</p>

<p style="font-size: 1.2rem"><code><%= link_to(@ips_url, @ips_url) %></code></p>

